---
Sepulchur Pasture is Midgaard's mass burial field, located south of the city gates beyond the ninth milestone.
Originally called the Ninth Acre, it was tended by shepherd-priests who rang a dusk bell to guide lost travelers through fog.
The oldest burial mounds contain worked stone fragments with eye-motifs matching the Watchers' Cairn, the pre-human circle marking Midgaard's founding site.
The field became an official civic burial site as war, dungeon, and caravan deaths exceeded the Temple of the Resounding Heart's crypt capacity.
Road dead were routed to the acre, names copied from signet rings or witness testimony, effects cataloged for return or forfeiture.
The Lantern Reforms extended processional lanes, waystones, and Bell Watch synchronization to the pasture as civic infrastructure.
The Last Burden Tithe — introduced during the Ash-and-Iron Decades — funded guards, carts, salt, and bells through a burial tariff.
The Tithe produced systematic inequity: families who paid received sanctified plots; those who could not were entered as "deferred names" in common furrows.
Deferred-name rolls have never been fully reconciled; the relevant year-ledgers from the Unindexed Years are missing or duplicated with different signatures.
The Violet Compact extended its containment doctrine to the pasture, establishing holding pens and wardwire trenches for plague-touched or arcane-active remains.
Night watch reports of the gravebell counting twice for every pull — once from the tower, once from somewhere beneath the furrows — marked the beginning of the pasture's institutional haunting.

